{{italic title}}
'''''De libero arbitrio''''' ('''''libri tres''''') ([[English language|English]]: '''''On Free Choice of the Will''''') is a book by [[Augustine of Hippo]] about the [[Free will in theology|freedom of will]]. Young Augustine wrote it in three volumes, one 387–389 in Rome, after his [[baptism]], and the other two between 391 and 395, after his priestly ordination in Africa.<ref>David E. Roberts: ''Augustine's Earliest Writings'', in: ''The Journal of Religion'', Vol. 33, No. 3, July 1953, p. 175.</ref>

The author started ''De libero arbitrio'' as a part of a series of works against [[Manichaeism]] and argued in favor of aspects of [[Scepticism]]. Augustine challenged [[Determinism]] in the first volume and investigated the conditions of the existence of God and knowledge in the other two parts.<ref>Henry Chadwick: ''Augustine'' in: Frances Margaret Young, Lewis Ayres, Andrew Louth: ''The Cambridge History of Early Christian Literature'', CUP, Cambridge 2004, pp. 330–331.</ref>

