'''Thomas Cleveland Holt''' (born November 30, 1942) is an American Historian; he is the [[James Westfall Thompson]] Professor of American and African American History at the [[University of Chicago]]. He has produced a number of works on the people and descendants of the [[African Diaspora]].<ref>[http://home.uchicago.edu/~tholt/index2.html Thomas C. Holt biography], The University of Chicago.</ref><ref>[http://history.uchicago.edu/directory/thomas-c-holt Thomas C. Holt], Department of History, The University of Chicago.</ref>
He taught at [[Howard University]], [[Harvard University]], the [[University of California, Berkeley]], and the [[University of Michigan]].<ref>[http://www.thomascholt.com/teaching.html Thomas C. Holt.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702063817/http://www.thomascholt.com/teaching.html |date=2007-07-02 }}</ref> He was born in [[Danville, Virginia]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EJvWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Holt,+Thomas+Cleveland%22&dq=%22Holt,+Thomas+Cleveland%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=v4gyT6W-IITciQKo8rWoCg&ved=0CEwQ6AEwBQ "Holt, Thomas Cleveland"], ''Reports of the President and of the Treasurer'', John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation, 1988, p. 53.</ref> He was elected a Member of the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2016.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160513163439/https://amphilsoc.org/members/electedApril2016</ref>
==Awards== A past president of the [[American Historical Association]], Holt was a Fellow of the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] and the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] from 1987 to 1988. Holt became a [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] Fellow in 1990.<ref>John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, [http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.1142703/k.787E/Fellows_List__August_1990.htm Fellows List] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307004157/http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.1142703/k.787E/Fellows_List__August_1990.htm |date=2012-03-07 }}</ref> In 1994, President [[Bill Clinton]] named Holt to the National Council on Humanities.<ref>[http://chronicle.uchicago.edu/940818/holt.shtml "Holt named to National Council on Humanities"], ''University of Chicago Chronicle'', Vol. 14, No. 2, August 18, 1994.</ref> He was elected a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2003.<ref>American Academy of Arts and Sciences, [http://www.amacad.org/members/new2003list.aspx Class of 2003 - Fellows]</ref> Holt was a Citigroup Fellow at the ''[[American Academy in Berlin]]'', Germany, for fall 2008.<ref>American Academy in Berlin, [http://www.americanacademy.de/home/alumni/detailansicht/person//fellow/thomas_holt/312/detail/ Citigroup Fellow Class of Fall 2008: Thomas Holt]</ref> In 1978 Holt was awarded the [[Southern Historical Association]]'s Charles S. Sydnor Prize for his first book, ''Black Over White''.<ref>[http://sha.uga.edu/awards/sydnor.htm "Awards — The Charles S. Sydnor Award"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513211933/http://sha.uga.edu/awards/sydnor.htm |date=2016-05-13 }}, The Southern Historical Association.</ref>
==Works== * [https://books.google.com/books?id=nI6vKvIR18cC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Thomas+Cleveland+Holt&cd=1#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Problem of Freedom: Race, Labor, and Politics in Jamaica and Britain, 1832-1938''], ([[Johns Hopkins University Press]]) in 1992, which won the [[Elsa Goveia]] Prize awarded by the Association of Caribbean Historians. * [https://books.google.com/books?id=LIqiqdeHMscC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Thomas+Cleveland+Holt&source=gbs_book_other_versions#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Black Over White: Negro Political Leadership in South Carolina During Reconstruction''] ([[University of Illinois Press]]). * "Nathan I. Huggins Lectures", ''The Problem of Race in the 21st Century'' ([[Harvard University Press]]) 2000 * [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rG1Q-3f5J4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Thomas+Cleveland+Holt&source=bl&ots=QDA58S4694&sig=vErwJzi2jPdyA9RS3Z2aEpeHEq0&hl=en&ei=Hk3GS6PUC4G49QSx88miDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Beyond Slavery: Explorations of Race, Labor, and Citizenship in Postemancipation Societies''], Authors Frederick Cooper, Thomas Cleveland Holt, Rebecca Jarvis Scott, UNC Press, 2000, {{ISBN|978-0-8078-4854-8}}. * [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rG1Q-3f5J4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Thomas+Cleveland+Holt&source=bl&ots=QDA58S4694&sig=vErwJzi2jPdyA9RS3Z2aEpeHEq0&hl=en&ei=Hk3GS6PUC4G49QSx88miDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Children of Fire: a History of African Americans''] ([[Hill & Wang]]) 2010
